04535nam a22006375i 9780226640716DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20202019ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2018061749  a97802266407167 a10.7208/97802266407162doi  a(DE-B1597)568326  a(OCoLC)1198931409  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aD16.8.H49bS77 2019 4aD16.8.H49bS77 2019 7aPHI0000002bisacsh04a9012231 aStrauss, Leo, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLeo Strauss on Hegel /cLeo Strauss; ed. by Paul Franco. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2020] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (384 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Leo Strauss Transcript Series00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tNote on the Leo Strauss Transcript Project -- tEditorial Headnote -- tIntroduction to the Transcript of Leo Strauss’s 1965 Course on Hegel’s Philosophy of History -- t1. Preliminary Considerations -- t2. Reason in History and the Nature of Spirit -- t3. The Actualization of Spirit in World History -- t4. Historical Understanding and the Folk- Mind -- t5. Africa and China -- t6. China Continued and India -- t7. India Continued and Persia -- t8. Phoenicia, Judea, and Egypt -- t9. The Greek World -- t10. The Greek World Continued -- t11. The Greek World Continued and the Roman World -- t12. The Roman World Continued and the Advent of Christianity -- t13. Interlude -- t14. The Middle Ages -- t15. The Middle Ages Continued -- t16 .The Reformation, Enlightenment, and French Revolution -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the winter of 1965, Leo Strauss taught a seminar on Hegel at the University of Chicago. While Strauss neither considered himself a Hegelian nor wrote about Hegel at any length, his writings contain intriguing references to the philosopher, particularly in connection with his studies of Hobbes, in his debate in On Tyranny with Alexandre Kojève; and in his account of the “three waves” of modern political philosophy. Leo Strauss on Hegel reconstructs Strauss’s seminar on Hegel, supplemented by passages from an earlier version of the seminar from which only fragments of a transcript remain. Strauss focused his seminar on the lectures collected in The Philosophy of History, which he considered more accessible than Hegel’s written works. In his own lectures on Hegel, Strauss continues his project of demonstrating how modern philosophers related to ancient thought and explores the development and weaknesses of modern political theory. Strauss is especially concerned with the relationship in Hegel between empirical history and his philosophy of history, and he argues for the primacy of religion in Hegel’s understanding of history and society. In addition to a relatively complete transcript, Leo Strauss on Hegel also includes annotations, which bring context and clarity to the text.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aHistoryxPhilosophy. 0aPhilosophy, German. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh  aHegel.  aKojève.  aStrauss.  ahistory.  aliberalism.  areligion.  atotalitarianism.1 aFranco, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFranco, Paul, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311071194340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226640716423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226640716.jpg  a978-3-11-071194-3  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  aGBV-deGruyter-alles